18
00:01:06,252 --> 00:01:07,473
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, President Morrell.

19
00:01:08,934 --> 00:01:23,428
[SPEAKER_02]: So tonight we're going to discuss proposed updates to Medford solid waste ordinance and this is, we're getting towards the tail end of what I'll told has been a fairly, a fairly long term project if you trace it back to its beginnings.

20
00:01:25,148 --> 00:01:35,091
[SPEAKER_02]: with the discussions on the solid waste task force which were convened to be discussing how to make sure that the city's next waste hauler contract is the best one for the city in every way.

21
00:01:35,492 --> 00:01:46,595
[SPEAKER_02]: During that discussion with a group of stakeholders which included myself and other community residents, some strategy consultants as well as Commissioner McGivern and Director Hunt.

22
00:01:47,595 --> 00:02:03,282
[SPEAKER_02]: One of the many recommendations that came out of that process was that it would be advantageous for us to pair the request for proposals for a new waste hauler contract with some updates to our solid waste ordinance to align it better with current state best practices.

23
00:02:03,322 --> 00:02:07,044
[SPEAKER_02]: So this ordinance revision process is kind of an out shoot of that.

24
00:02:09,044 --> 00:02:13,746
[SPEAKER_02]: Where we started was with some mass DEP template language that's recommended for

25
00:02:15,327 --> 00:02:21,850
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, just municipalities across the state to bring them into alignment with current best practices for waste hauling in Massachusetts.

26
00:02:21,890 --> 00:02:29,713
[SPEAKER_02]: This includes essentially better modern language for aligning municipal waste hauling practices with

27
00:02:32,201 --> 00:02:40,829
[SPEAKER_02]: to bring communities closer to zero waste and keep things streamlined and align with the current, certain current waste bands of which there are several.

28
00:02:41,129 --> 00:02:42,230
[SPEAKER_02]: So that was our starting place.

29
00:02:43,171 --> 00:02:51,079
[SPEAKER_02]: The Solid Waste Ordinance as it's currently on the books is clearly was written several decades ago.

30
00:02:51,119 --> 00:02:54,762
[SPEAKER_02]: I think as we find often when we're doing these ordinance revision projects, it's just that there's a lot of

31
00:02:55,763 --> 00:03:00,465
[SPEAKER_02]: pretty dated language to clean up, not just to modernize it, but to make it actually more useful.

32
00:03:00,505 --> 00:03:07,248
[SPEAKER_02]: And in this case, useful, not just for city staff, but also for contractors that the city has to work with and residents and businesses.

33
00:03:07,728 --> 00:03:08,889
[SPEAKER_02]: So that is a big piece of it.

34
00:03:09,249 --> 00:03:16,392
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the other major chunk is just updating the solid waste ordinance so that it is in alignment with current state best practices.

35
00:03:16,412 --> 00:03:22,815
[SPEAKER_02]: And again, this is to help us be positioned to get the most advantageous solid waste and recycling

36
00:03:23,815 --> 00:03:37,724
[SPEAKER_02]: contract that we can both in the short term and in the long term to just improve that foundation, make it more legible for residents and businesses to perceive like who should be doing what.

37
00:03:40,066 --> 00:03:44,509
[SPEAKER_02]: And then I also had a third thing but I forgot what it was.

38
00:03:44,849 --> 00:03:45,849
[SPEAKER_02]: So I'll also mention that

