66
00:06:40,678 --> 00:06:53,965
[SPEAKER_02]: So I'll certainly pause for questions and additional comments at the end, but if any requests for clarification come up while I'm zipping through it, just wave at me.

67
00:06:56,974 --> 00:07:03,157
[SPEAKER_02]: So we took care to try to align this updated ordinance with what's currently in our Code of Ordinances.

68
00:07:04,778 --> 00:07:14,623
[SPEAKER_02]: Most of what is currently in the ordinances just deals with what is waste in Medford and what should we do and not do with it.

69
00:07:16,203 --> 00:07:21,626
[SPEAKER_02]: So at the beginning here, Article 1, a lot of this is still in Medford.

70
00:07:22,567 --> 00:07:29,392
[SPEAKER_02]: the current standing language that we use for removal of waste material or debris and section 72 kind of goes on.

71
00:07:29,572 --> 00:07:38,898
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll have some suggestions later on in the meeting for how to update this language because it's some of the kind of last remaining difficult to understand language in the ordinance.

72
00:07:40,179 --> 00:07:44,302
[SPEAKER_02]: This is essentially saying, you know, hey, people of Medford, don't leave trash in the streets.

73
00:07:45,916 --> 00:08:05,958
[SPEAKER_02]: Then we get into Article 2, and this is where we took the most guidance from the MAS DEP template language and guidance from the task force and our subject matter experts on how to have this help manifest a better waste hauling system in Medford and better conditions for future waste hauling RFPs.

74
00:08:09,848 --> 00:08:14,472
[SPEAKER_02]: This is really similar language that we see to a lot of other municipalities in Massachusetts.

75
00:08:16,354 --> 00:08:25,302
[SPEAKER_02]: This ordinance establishes minimum requirements for the systemic collection of solid waste and recyclables in order to comply with state mandated waste bans along those lines.

76
00:08:26,284 --> 00:08:36,687
[SPEAKER_02]: It defines people and things related to waste in Medford, such as commercial generators of waste, residential generators of waste, leaf collection.

77
00:08:37,588 --> 00:08:49,952
[SPEAKER_02]: It points to several state level waste hauling related things like the Mercury Disposal Prohibition Act, all of these sort of state level acts and requirements that municipalities have to also adhere to.

78
00:08:52,717 --> 00:08:53,139
[SPEAKER_02]: et cetera.

79
00:08:53,159 --> 00:08:57,119
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm not going to bother going through all of these, but feel free to pause me.

80
00:08:59,913 --> 00:09:14,143
[SPEAKER_02]: In discussions in subcommittee, we decided that it would make sense to have this updated ordinance go into effect on July 1st, 2024, because that is the likely date that a new waste hauling contract would go into effect.

81
00:09:14,603 --> 00:09:28,052
[SPEAKER_02]: So it makes sense to have that align with when either a new hauler or a new contract is actually starting work in Medford, so that there wouldn't be sort of a messy overlap of waste haulers having to change their standards in the middle of a contract or at a seemingly arbitrary time.

82
00:09:29,875 --> 00:09:41,265
[SPEAKER_02]: Something that is also newly articulated in these proposed changes is it makes it much more clear that recycling is mandatory in Medford and how that will happen.

83
00:09:42,766 --> 00:09:53,256
[SPEAKER_02]: The previous version of the ordinance was not very clear on, I personally feel that there is some contradictory language around how mandatory it is and where the burden for doing that falls.

84
00:09:55,385 --> 00:10:07,033
[SPEAKER_02]: So first section in this division, in order to protect the environment, promote recycling and be in compliance with based around regulations, we establish a requirement for the mandatory separation of recyclables from the solid waste stream.

85
00:10:07,053 --> 00:10:12,276
[SPEAKER_02]: And the city will inform all generators at least once per year that recycling is mandatory.

86
00:10:13,357 --> 00:10:20,902
[SPEAKER_02]: It goes through which departments are responsible for promulgating requirements and standards around

87
00:10:21,643 --> 00:10:35,367
[SPEAKER_02]: what trash and recycling is picked up and how, so here it points to Commissioner of Public Works for container requirements, how recycling should be separated, separating leaves and yard waste, composting should that become more relevant.

88
00:10:37,874 --> 00:10:40,476
[SPEAKER_02]: Then it goes into the permit that is required for haulers.

89
00:10:40,516 --> 00:10:43,017
[SPEAKER_02]: This is also substantially updated.

90
00:10:43,037 --> 00:10:53,804
[SPEAKER_02]: A lot of this just makes it clear what of the permit requirements point to the Board of Health, since the Board of Health promulgates permits for solid waste haulers.

91
00:10:57,286 --> 00:11:01,028
[SPEAKER_02]: So this kind of creates signals for waste haulers.

92
00:11:01,990 --> 00:11:07,072
[SPEAKER_02]: that this is a process that goes through the Board of Health, is overseen by the Board of Health, enforced by the Board of Health.

93
00:11:08,513 --> 00:11:17,918
[SPEAKER_02]: And there are some new measures in here, which are also recommended by the state around how haulers must,

94
00:11:20,463 --> 00:11:26,027
[SPEAKER_02]: log and record how much solid waste and recycling they are picking up from each generator per year.

95
00:11:27,087 --> 00:11:41,597
[SPEAKER_02]: This is to allow municipalities to better track our progress towards waste reduction, which is something that is very aligned with many of our city's other plans, progress towards zero waste and the Climate Action and Adaptation Plan.

96
00:11:42,938 --> 00:11:47,780
[SPEAKER_02]: This is also something that I think is just very useful information for a city to have for a lot of purposes.

97
00:11:47,880 --> 00:12:03,908
[SPEAKER_02]: I think the thing that I probably forgot to say at the top is that one of the reasons it's really good for us to update our practices and better aligned with overall state best practices is that doing so makes the city more eligible for more state funding to offset the cost of waste hauling in Medford.

98
00:12:04,428 --> 00:12:07,930
[SPEAKER_02]: So passing and then enforcing this ordinance will do that and also

99
00:12:08,851 --> 00:12:21,889
[SPEAKER_02]: Using the leverage and the new standards in it to hasten our progress towards zero waste also puts us in a better position to, you know, essentially be receiving grant assistance to pay for the cost of waste hauling and hauling adjacent things.

100
00:12:24,790 --> 00:12:27,352
[SPEAKER_02]: Next, bundled service requirement.

101
00:12:27,733 --> 00:12:36,040
[SPEAKER_02]: We've discussed this in our meetings around the request for proposals for the new waste hauling contract as well, and this is really aligned with the goals in there.

102
00:12:36,901 --> 00:12:51,153
[SPEAKER_02]: This makes it clear that waste haulers that are seeking a permit to work in Medford must provide solid waste collection, sorry, if they're providing solid waste collection, they must also provide recyclables collection.

103
00:12:51,453 --> 00:12:55,575
[SPEAKER_02]: If you want to haul waste in Medford, if you're going to pick up trash, you also have to pick up recycling.

104
00:12:56,355 --> 00:13:00,016
[SPEAKER_02]: There's a provision that if you want to only pick up recycling, you can do that.

105
00:13:01,137 --> 00:13:10,720
[SPEAKER_02]: But essentially, this is to try to make sure it stays cost effective for every generator of waste in Medford, no matter what type of building that is, to get recycling service.

106
00:13:13,461 --> 00:13:17,263
[SPEAKER_02]: Enforcement goes back into what departments oversee what parts of the ordinance.

107
00:13:18,225 --> 00:13:21,266
[SPEAKER_02]: The Board of Health can inspect trucks.

108
00:13:21,466 --> 00:13:26,606
[SPEAKER_02]: They also issue regulations around violations of the ordinance.

109
00:13:26,666 --> 00:13:28,527
[SPEAKER_02]: They're kind of the enforcing body for much of this.

110
00:13:31,727 --> 00:13:40,289
[SPEAKER_02]: Here we have kind of more on the permit side, points to penalties that are overseen by the Board of Health for any failures to adhere to the permitting requirements.

111
00:13:43,209 --> 00:13:44,009
[SPEAKER_03]: That's the overview.

