150
00:17:10,757 --> 00:17:13,558
[SPEAKER_00]: One of them they thought was interesting.

151
00:17:13,778 --> 00:17:21,080
[SPEAKER_00]: One was from a national organization, NWRA, which, sorry, I have to keep flipping to see what

152
00:17:21,390 --> 00:17:25,953
[SPEAKER_00]: things stand for national waste, da, da, da.

153
00:17:26,714 --> 00:17:37,441
[SPEAKER_00]: But basically their comment was that they really wanna see things pushed onto the generators rather than on the haulers for enforcement.

154
00:17:37,881 --> 00:17:39,522
[SPEAKER_00]: Of course, we like to see them both.

155
00:17:40,083 --> 00:17:50,650
[SPEAKER_00]: DEP points out that our ordinance actually has penalties for both the people who generate the waste and the people who haul the waste, and that that is very helpful

156
00:17:51,762 --> 00:18:06,834
[SPEAKER_00]: DEP also let us know that the standards that they put together, this draft template, the policies from the state were actually all developed in conjunction with this national organization, National Waste and Recycling Association.

157
00:18:08,415 --> 00:18:15,560
[SPEAKER_00]: However, that the executive director of said organization has turned over since they worked with them.

158
00:18:16,032 --> 00:18:30,122
[SPEAKER_00]: And it's quite possible that the person who submitted the letter to us was not aware of the extensive outreach and stakeholder engagement that the state went through to develop this template and their recommendations to the city.

159
00:18:31,183 --> 00:18:41,390
[SPEAKER_00]: So they just really wanted to, the state wanted us to look at and point out that we are actually have fines in here on both ends.

160
00:18:41,490 --> 00:18:42,791
[SPEAKER_00]: If you put out the wrong stuff,

161
00:18:43,665 --> 00:18:45,426
[SPEAKER_00]: recycle correctly kind of things.

162
00:18:45,646 --> 00:18:48,808
[SPEAKER_00]: Those could be fine as well as the hauling.

163
00:18:50,869 --> 00:19:00,333
